<font color="#FF0000">WHY ARE VETERANS NEGLECTED?</font><br>
<tt>Fri Mar 14 21:59:05 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Alex,<br><br>
Why do people agree to fight for this country when we have such a long history of neglecting veterans who have made ultimate sacrifices, taken ultimate personal risks, and sufferred ultimate horrors and injuries to defend this country?  Is it any wonder that the draft was met with such scorn?  In light of what you have said, how can we blame anybody for burning their draft card or moving to Canada to avoid the draft? It sounds like the U.S. treats its soldiers like objects to be used, abused, and then tossed out.  So then, what *are* the priorities and values of those who send the soldiers into war?  If they're all about protecting human rights and U.S. citizens, why do they so quickly forget about the rights of those citizens who fought?  Why are they not protected, taken care of?  Who then, are they really out to protect?  If you ask me, they are out for the protection of power and status quo.  That is all that war ever has been about and ever will be.  Perhaps WWII was defensive, but in general it looks like most wars, 'police actions', 'military interventions', or whatever euphemism you prefer, are not about humanity, but rather power.  Otherwise you'd think the veterans of those wars might be treated with some humanity.<br><br>
I don't know how original my thoughts are.  To an extent all thoughts are plagarized if you use words you didn't coin, since what are words but abstract representations of thought?  All I can tell you is that I honestly believe with great conviction everything I've said, and I have thought it all through very carefully over many many years.  My thoughts were formed from reading, talking to others, etc., but they feel like my own.<br><br>
Arthur, no problem, and you hit the nail on the head.<br><br>
Chris
